 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ualedar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aledar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Channeler</span><br>  Posts: 181<br> <font color=#ffffff>(2/6/02 11:40 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: It's depressing</span><hr size=1> It's funny, most melees I know are bitching that we casters are out of our minds complaining, that Luclin truely is a caster expansion.  All these new mobs have extremely high AC... they're only getting 65-75 DPS on average as a result.<br>
<br>
And here I am sitting there, wondering if I should tell them that with my epic, familiar, Kaodics, FT items, and so forth, being one of the best equipped wizards on my server, with loot from NToV and all three Velious kings and so forth, will only hold steady at 30 DPS.  I kinda do want to tell them that our damage output is bad... to laugh at the SK's and Paladins who wine that they're only getting 70 DPS in exp groups and that warriors have too much of an advantage over them, to roll my eyes that the rogues are upset because the best equipped rogue is only doing 137 DPS compared to a monk's 125 DPS... but will they ever invite me for a group again if they found that out?<br>
<br>
But here's the problem.  If you jack up either our spell damage or mana regen to close the gap, we'd simply become FAR too overpowered in raid situations.  That, plus wizards can almost hold even with melee exp if they quad kite, and maybe go a bit faster if they AE.  But if you keep it the way things are, wizards will continue to get shunned from groups, because our only real role is to do damage, which we ain't doing.  And quad kiting hour after hour gets very boring.<br>
<br>
The sad part is, our DPS increases by about 50% with the Velk robe, and almost 100% with the VP robe.  It's come to the point where a VP robe is almost required to fill your role in an exp group.  It was all good and stuff up until 50, things were overall balanced (in a non-twinked environment, but that's a whole other issue), but the gap got insane as you head towards 60.  And there's really not much you can do to balance it at this point, it just got that out of hand, and will totally mess with the balance of the &quot;end game&quot;.  Because you can't really compare our damage output on raids, because we can store up damage for a big fight, but be pretty worthless for 10 minutes after when it doesn't matter.  Melee damage is pretty constant on the other hand.  Big advantage to us on raids, but big big disadvantage in exp groups.<br>
<br>
Looking back at 46-60, I spent a significant amount of my time soloing, or duoing with my close shaman friend.  Relying on pickup groups lead me to retire my wizard for a month or two, and my chanter shot up in levels... only raiding with a couple close friends held my interest on my wizard, until I finially hit 60 and got to spend almost all my time raiding.  Most of the wizards I know spent most of their time quad kiting to 60, not because they wanted to, but as a lack of options.  Those that didn't, got PL'ed by their level 60 melee and cleric friends during free time.<br>
<br>
In the end, you play the game to have fun.  I simply didn't have fun exp grinding, it's just not fun to sit there LFG for hours, and on those occasions where friends do get you in a group, feeling guilty that you can't even do what your class is supposed to do.  Yeah, I know, we can be valuable by a well timed root on an overpull, or absorbing some minor damage, but in the end, I often felt a tad lacking.  Raids, on the other hand, are fun, and are what keeps me playing the game.  Too bad I feel like it was a chore for all those months post-50 actually getting to 60.  But once I got there, I'm having the time of my life.  And then they had to go and add AA. =/<br>
<br>
I do like my wizard, after all, I'm still playing him, and am enjoying it now.  I just wish I knew about the grouping situation we would undergo when I first started him, the day I bought the game.  Sure, I am the master of magical damage... on raids.  How often does your common, everyday player spend raiding boss mobs?  I guess that's why most of my wizard friends pretty much hit a dead end at the low 50's, and now have warriors and monks shooting up in levels like mad.<br>
<br>
We're a raiding class, period.  We just have to face up to that fact.<br>
<br>
Just my thoughts. <p><a href="http://www.reconstructed.nu/profile.php?pid=119">Baron Aledar Boomcaster</a><br>Sorcerer of <a href="http://www.reconstructed.nu/">Reconstructed</a>, E'ci<br><img src="http://www.seas.upenn.edu/~bwa/kerasig.jpg"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/usaradin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Saradin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer</span><br>  Posts: 1199<br> <font color=#ffffff>(2/6/02 11:44 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: It's depressing</span><hr size=1> Throw me in the silver lining group, but rather than rehashing what the already said, I will say this...<br>
<br>
Start a Monk! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
They are a lot of fun. I thoroughly enjoy playing both my Wizard and my Monk. Let the Ebayers go to Legends, good riddance to 'em. I could care less about Legends, it doesn't phase me in the least because I know that once a good game comes I am there. I have a pretty keen eye for good games, and I have not jumped on AO, DAoC, or the others.<br>
<br>
But I will say that WoW is looking promising, and I cannot wait to see what Blizzard can come up with. The good (and bad) part is that they will take a long time building the game to make sure it is done right.<br>
<br>
But only we can be the judge of that...<br>
till then, this gamer is playing EQ. <p><p align="center">
